Consider a wavefront of a light wave when it passes across a straight boundary from a vacuum into a transparent substance.<br><img src="./factsheet-physics/media/8"><br><ul><li>The wavefront moves from <i>XY</i> to <i>X'Y'</i> in time <i>t</i>.</li></ul><div>In this time, the wavefront moves</div><div><ul><li>A distance <i>ct</i>&nbsp;at speed&nbsp;<i>c</i>&nbsp;in a vacuum from&nbsp;<i>Y</i>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<i>Y'</i>&nbsp;</li><li>A distance&nbsp;<i>c<sub>s</sub>t</i>&nbsp;at speed&nbsp;<i>c<sub>s</sub>&nbsp;</i>in the substance from <i>X</i> to <i>X'</i>&nbsp;</li></ul><div>Giving us equations\[\begin{align*}
ct&amp;=XY'\sin i\\
c_st&amp;=XY'\sin r\\
\end{align*}\]Combining these equations give</div></div><div>\[\frac{\sin i}{\sin r}=\frac{c}{c_s}\]<br></div>